    <node id="1. The Liberal party blocked debate on expanding the wage subsidy program and refused to allow certain businesses that made acquisitions to access the program: Based on the transcripts, it is not explicitly stated why the Liberals blocked the debate on expanding the wage subsidy program or refused access to certain businesses that made acquisitions. However, it can be inferred that there may have been political disagreements between the Liberal and Conservative parties, as they both criticize each other for not wanting to debate the legislation.&#10;2. The rent relief program remains difficult to apply for and has only distributed a small fraction of its allocated funds to date: The transcripts mention that the Canada emergency commercial rent assistance (CECRA) program has only paid out less than 2% of its $3 billion budgeted as of June 8, despite being available for application since mid-May. Some businesses and landlords find it difficult to apply for this program, which has resulted in many not bothering to apply and leaving small businesses to fall through the cracks.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Liberal party blocked debate on expanding the wage subsidy program while criticizing the Conservatives for not wanting to debate the legislation. Meanwhile, the rent relief program has only distributed a small fraction of its allocated funds due to difficulty in applying for the program and lack of interest from landlords." />
