    <node id=" Hon. David Lametti (Minister of Justice and Attorney General of Canada)&#10;Content: Mr. Chair, Canada's forestry industry supports good middle-class jobs in communities across our country. The sector is also an essential link in the medical equipment supply chain, and we thank them for all the work they're doing. We're aware of the immense pressures faced by this sector, especially at this time, and Deputy Prime Minister Freeland and others are taking that seriously and working through this issue. As our government has said repeatedly, we firmly believe that the U.S. duties on Canadian softwood lumber are unfair and unwarranted, and we will pursue all means in order to&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: Before continuing, I want to remind honourable members who are at home to make sure that the boom on their headsets is down. It just makes a better pickup. We heard everything, but it was a little distant. That's for everyone's benefit. We're now going to continue with Mr.Deltell.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Grard Deltell (Louis-Saint-Laurent, CPC)&#10;Content: Mr.Chair, before I ask my question, I'd like to pay tribute to the Minister of Justice, particularly" />
    <node id="but-no-answer period. Let's try something else. The forestry industry was in crisis even before the pandemic, with mills closing down and thousands of jobs lost. Eight weeks ago, Minister Freeland said, I have had many discussions with leaders in our forestry sector and the provinces about what we can do to support the industry today. Meanwhile, we've had support going to the arts and we've had support going to fisheries, just to name a few, but arguably for the industry that was having some of the most numerous challenges, it has been radio silence. That was eight weeks ago today. Can the government at least commit to releasing an updated softwood lumber transition plan before we rise?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Seamus O'Regan (Minister of Natural Resources)&#10;Content: Mr. Chair, we remain committed, of course, to the forestry industry and seeing it through this pandemic and this very uncertain time. The expanding market opportunities program, for instance, has helped Canada's forestry sector diversify, create jobs and open new markets. We've had new construction projects that are active today, using Canadian wood in key markets like Korea, Japan, China and the United States. Tomorrow this House will vote on our government's investment of $" />
    <node id="The question is asking why the Canadian federal government cannot provide an economic update during the uncertain times of COVID-19, when some provinces like Quebec, Saskatchewan, and Newfoundland have been able to do so.&#10;&#10;Minister Mona Fortier, the Canadian Finance Minister, has stated that the Canadian economy is going through a period of extraordinary uncertainty due to COVID-19 and that the government will continue to be open and transparent about the actions it is taking to support families, businesses, workers, and the healthcare system. However, she has not provided a clear economic projection yet. The opposition parties have criticized the government for not providing an economic update, arguing that Canadians deserve to know the state of the economy, especially given the current uncertainty caused by the pandemic.&#10;&#10;Minister Fortier has mentioned the implementation of the economic action plan to respond to COVID-19 and the provision of immediate assistance to Canadians, businesses, and workers. She has also highlighted the support provided through interest-free loans to businesses and continued support for businesses and Canadians during this time. However, she has not provided a clear answer regarding the reason for not providing an economic update.&#10;&#10;The opposition parties, including MPs Cathy McLeod, Grard Deltell, and John Williamson, have criticized the government for not providing an economic update, arguing that Canadians deserve to know the state of the economy, especially given the current uncertainty caused by the pandemic. They have pointed out that other provinces are able to provide updates on their economies while carrying out their responsibilities.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Canadian federal government has not provided a clear answer regarding why they cannot provide an economic update during these uncertain times, despite calls from opposition parties and some provinces doing so. The Finance Minister has emphasized the government's commitment to transparency and supporting Canadians but has not given a timeline for when an economic projection may be provided." />
    <node id="1. Members are being reminded to bring their petitions to the table because it is a procedural rule of the House that petitions should be presented physically at the table when they are being discussed. This allows for a more formal and respectful acknowledgement of the petitioners' concerns.&#10;2. The petition tabled by Mr. Kevin Lamoureux calls on the government to assist the poorest seniors, specifically by increasing the Guaranteed Income Supplement (GIS) by $200 and the Old Age Security (OAS) by $300. This is a request for the government to provide additional financial support to low-income seniors, who may be struggling to make ends meet due to rising costs of living or inadequate retirement savings." />
    <node id=" to see us pass that bill as soon as possible.&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: Presenting petitions, Mr. Lamoureux.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Kevin Lamoureux (Winnipeg North, Lib.)&#10;Content: Thank you, Mr. Chair. It is with pleasure that I table another petition by the residents of Winnipeg North. These residents have signed a petition asking the Government of Canada, and in fact all members of Parliament, to put a high priority on assisting our poorest seniors. The increases to the GIS by $200, and $300 to the OAS, have been well received. They just want to highlight how important it is to support our seniors, in particular the poorest of our seniors.&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: For members present in the Chamber, a reminder that they are asked to bring their petitions to the table. We'll now proceed to statements by members. We'll go to Ms. Atwin for the first one.&#10;Speaker: Mrs. Jenica Atwin (Fredericton, GP)&#10;Content: Thank you, Mr. Chair. June 21 is National Indigenous Peoples Day, a day of acknowledgement and a day of celebration of the beautiful diversity of indigenous peoples" />
    <node id=" response on that issue, something it hasn't done in response to past petitions on this. The third petition deals with the issue of firearms. The petitioners want to see the government take a strong response in dealing with illegal guns and gun smuggling. The petition notes that the vast majority of firearms-related crimes in Canada involves illegal guns. At the same time, the petitioners are concerned that the government has the wrong focusthat is, harassing law-abiding firearms ownerswithout putting in place substantial measures to deal with illegal guns. The petitioners want to see the reversal of the order in council from May 1 and strong measures to deal with illegal firearms. The fourth and final petition deals with Bill S-204, a bill that would make it a criminal offence for a Canadian to go abroad and receive an organ from a person who has not consented to giving that organ. It would also create a mechanism by which someone could be deemed inadmissible to Canada if they were involved in organ harvesting and trafficking. The petitioners are supportive of Bill S-204 and of similar bills in previous parliaments and would like to see us pass that bill as soon as possible.&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: Presenting petitions, Mr. Lamoureux.&#10;" />
    <node id="Speaker: The Chair (Hon. Anthony Rota (NipissingTimiskaming, Lib.))&#10;Content: I call this meeting to order.  Welcome to the 23rd meeting of the House of Commons Special Committee on the COVID-19 Pandemic.  A reminder to all members that in order to avoid issues with sound, members participating in person should not also be connected to the video conference. For those of you who are joining via video conference, I will remind you that when speaking you should be on the same channel as the language you are speaking, and please use your headsets. As usual, please direct your remarks through the chair. As I understand, there are no ministerial announcements today.  We will now proceed to presenting petitions. I remind members that any petition presented during a meeting of this special committee must have already been certified by the clerk of petitions. For members participating in person, I ask that they please come and drop their signed certificates off at the table once the petition is presented. I would ask members to be very brief and concise, and to summarize the exact content of the petition. We will continue. The first person presenting a petition today is Ms. May.&#10;Speaker: Ms. Elizabeth May (SaanichG" />
    <node id="1) The Canadian government, led by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and Finance Minister Mona Fortier, is facing pressure from opposition parties to provide an economic update during the COVID-19 pandemic. Opposition MPs argue that Canadians deserve to know the state of the economy, especially given the current uncertainty caused by the pandemic and the pre-existing economic troubles prior to COVID-19.&#10;2) Minister Fortier has acknowledged the extraordinary uncertainty due to COVID-19 and stated that the government will continue to be open and transparent about its actions. However, she has not provided a clear economic projection yet. The opposition parties have criticized the government for not providing an economic update, while some provinces like Quebec, Saskatchewan, and Newfoundland have been able to provide updates on their economies.&#10;3) Minister Fortier emphasizes the government's commitment to transparency and supporting Canadians but has not given a clear reason or timeline for when an economic projection may be provided. The opposition parties argue that the government's refusal to provide an update is a sign of a lack of transparency and accountability." />
    <node id="1. The current challenge faced by creators in the music industry is the significant decline in their income, despite the increased accessibility of culture and music through digital technology. This paradox can be attributed to the way the digital technology revolution has disrupted the system for distributing wealth generated by creators, with various internet stakeholders, many of whom are billionaires, benefiting instead. The petition mentioned addresses this issue by proposing a minimum royalty model for streaming platforms and requesting that telecom providers share their profits with artists since they sell their services as direct access to culture.&#10;&#10;Additionally, the Canadian government has provided support measures tailored to the arts and culture sector's needs during the COVID-19 crisis. These include adapting the CERB to consider royalties and extending it for a more extended period, acknowledging that recovery in this sector may take longer (Hon. Steven Guilbeault). The government is also consulting with arts and culture stakeholders to develop long-term solutions, though details of these efforts have not been disclosed yet (Hon. Steven Guilbeault).&#10;&#10;The challenges faced by creators in the music industry highlight a pressing need for fair compensation models that adequately reflect the value of their work in the digital era and address the issues arising from digital technology's impact on wealth distribution within the cultural ecosystem." />
    <node id="ically, creators' incomes have never been so low. The advent of digital technology has completely overturned the system for distributing the wealth generated by creators for the benefit of various Web stakeholders, many of whom are billionaires. This petition addresses these problems and proposes realistic solutions. The first is to set a minimum royalty model for streaming platforms for artists. The second is to update the existing private copying system. The third is for Internet and cell phone providers who sell their services as direct access to culture to share their profits with artists. The fourth is that the GAFAMs have to pay taxes on their services. Six thousand people have already signed the first version of this petition, launched last month by musician JordanOfficer and supported by singer BarbaraSecours. As an artist, I am proud to present this petition today because the issues it raises are fundamental to the survival of Quebec culture.&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: We'll now continue with Mr. Genuis.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Garnett Genuis (Sherwood ParkFort Saskatchewan, CPC)&#10;Content: Thank you very much, Mr. Chair. I have four petitions to present today. I will be as brief as you suggested, although I will observe that if some members are going on longer" />
