    <edge source="Based on the transcripts provided, the question you are asking was posed to the Prime Minister by the Leader of the Opposition. The Liberal party, led by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, has been criticized for blocking debate on expanding the wage subsidy program and refusing access to certain businesses that made acquisitions. However, it is not explicitly stated why the Liberals took this stance. The transcripts suggest that there may have been political disagreements between the Liberal and Conservative parties.&#10;&#10;To answer your question directly, the Prime Minister has not yet indicated any plans to adjust the criteria of the wage subsidy program to allow companies who have made acquisitions to qualify. This is something that the Leader of the Opposition has called for in order to prevent further lapsing of allocated funds and help more people stay employed. However, as of now, there has been no official response from the Prime Minister on this matter." target="Laurent, CPC)&#10;Content: Mr.Chair, before I ask my question, I'd like to pay tribute to the Minister of Justice, particularly to his versatility. Today, he talked about forests. Yesterday, the Minister of Justice talked about Davie and indigenous affairs. Really, this minister is very versatile. My question is directly for the Minister of Finance. I like Mr.Lametti very much, but I'd like Mr.Morneau to answer my question. Yesterday, in a Senate parliamentary committee, the Minister of Finance half-opened the door to an economic update. Based on what he said, it seems that, as we speak, a committee of the Department of Finance is working on an economic update. Could Mr.Morneau tell Canadians when he is going to table this economic update?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Mona Fortier&#10;Content: Mr.Chair, as we know, the Canadian economy is going through a period of extraordinary uncertainty. As soon as it's possible to provide clear economic projections, we will provide a full update to Canadians. Right now, we can say that we have supported workers, businesses and Canadians with the emergency measures we have put in place. We will continue to do so, because we need">
