    <edge source="Based on the transcripts provided, the question you are asking was posed to the Prime Minister by the Leader of the Opposition. The Liberal party, led by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, has been criticized for blocking debate on expanding the wage subsidy program and refusing access to certain businesses that made acquisitions. However, it is not explicitly stated why the Liberals took this stance. The transcripts suggest that there may have been political disagreements between the Liberal and Conservative parties.&#10;&#10;To answer your question directly, the Prime Minister has not yet indicated any plans to adjust the criteria of the wage subsidy program to allow companies who have made acquisitions to qualify. This is something that the Leader of the Opposition has called for in order to prevent further lapsing of allocated funds and help more people stay employed. However, as of now, there has been no official response from the Prime Minister on this matter." target="Based on the transcripts provided, the question you are asking was posed by a member of parliament to the Minister of Employment, Workforce Development and Disability Inclusion. The member brought up the case of Krystal, a community worker who is taking care of her child and vulnerable father during the COVID-19 pandemic. Krystal's employer has asked her to return to work or take a leave, but she is uncomfortable returning to work due to safety concerns. Service Canada has not given Krystal a clear answer on whether collecting CERB while refusing a reasonable job offer would be considered fraudulent. The member asked what measures the minister is taking to ensure clear guidance for Canadians and Service Canada agents regarding eligibility for the CERB, while respecting provincial workplace health and safety regulations and an individual's right to refuse work in unsafe conditions.&#10;&#10;The Minister of Employment, Workforce Development and Disability Inclusion responded by stating that they recognize workers will face various different situations during the pandemic and that workers have the right not to work in unsafe situations. The minister also stated that many Canadians do want to go back to work and that they will continue to support Canadians throughout the recovery process.&#10;&#10;Later on, the member asked again for a clear answer on whether Krystal can continue receiving CERB without being accused of fraud if she refuses to return to work due to safety concerns. The Minister responded by stating that if a Canadian has to take care of a loved one due to circumstances surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic, they are indeed eligible to receive the CERB and remain receiving that benefit.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Minister has assured Canadians who need to take care of loved ones due to circumstances surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic that they can continue receiving the CERB benefit without being accused of fraud. However, it is not explicitly stated what measures the minister is taking to ensure clear guidance for Canadians and Service Canada agents regarding eligibility for the CERB while respecting provincial workplace health and safety regulations and an individual's right to refuse work in unsafe conditions.">
      <data key="d0">1</data>
