    <edge source="Based on the transcripts provided, the question you are asking was posed to the Prime Minister by the Leader of the Opposition. The Liberal party, led by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, has been criticized for blocking debate on expanding the wage subsidy program and refusing access to certain businesses that made acquisitions. However, it is not explicitly stated why the Liberals took this stance. The transcripts suggest that there may have been political disagreements between the Liberal and Conservative parties.&#10;&#10;To answer your question directly, the Prime Minister has not yet indicated any plans to adjust the criteria of the wage subsidy program to allow companies who have made acquisitions to qualify. This is something that the Leader of the Opposition has called for in order to prevent further lapsing of allocated funds and help more people stay employed. However, as of now, there has been no official response from the Prime Minister on this matter." target="1. Based on the transcript provided, it is not explicitly stated whether the deputy minister provided the minister with an appropriate written plan within a month of the commitment. While Hon. Lawrence MacAulay mentions that they have indicated that addressing the backlog is a major priority and that they are able to attack the problem in an appropriate manner with the allocated funds, he does not confirm if a written plan has been provided. MP Alex Ruff continues to ask for this written plan throughout the transcript, indicating that it may not have been received at the time of the conversation.&#10;2. Regarding the appropriateness of the plan, Mr. Alex Ruff expresses his confidence in the deputy minister's ability to produce an appropriate written plan. However, he questions the minister's hesitation in confirming its existence. This could suggest that there might be some discrepancies between what the minister perceives as an appropriate plan and what Mr. Ruff is expecting.&#10;&#10;In summary, while it is unclear if the deputy minister provided the minister with a written plan within a month of the commitment, MP Alex Ruff's continued questioning suggests that this might not be the case. Furthermore, there might be some disagreement between Mr. Ruff and the minister regarding what constitutes an appropriate plan to address the backlog.">
