    <edge source=" RCMP. If the Prime Minister really wants to act, why is he delaying the action plan in response to the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Bill Blair&#10;Content: Let me assure this House and the member opposite that we're not dragging our feet. This is an important issue. Indigenous people, black Canadians and other racialized people are far too often experiencing systemic racism and disparate outcomes through the criminal justice system. It's incumbent upon all of us who work within the criminal justice system to take the steps and actions necessary to produce more equitable outcomes. All police services, including the RCMP, must be committed to ensuring that the people they're sworn to serve and protect are always treated with dignity and respect.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Alexandre Boulerice&#10;Content: MadamChair, why are the Liberals taking indigenous children to court to challenge the Canadian Human Rights Tribunal ruling in their favour?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Marc Miller (Minister of Indigenous Services)&#10;Content: Madam Chair, as the honourable member knows full well, a number of cases are pending, and we are currently negotiating with the parties. We are making progress, and I would be delighted to tell the member and the House about" target="1. The Liberal government, led by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, has not yet committed to a review of the RCMP budget with the specific intention of reallocating resources to community services and addressing systemic racism, as requested by Black Lives Matter and other advocates.&#10;2. Despite acknowledging the presence of systemic racism within the criminal justice system, including the RCMP, and recognizing the need for equitable outcomes for Indigenous people, black Canadians, and other racialized people, the Liberal government has not taken any concrete steps to implement reforms or an action plan related to the National Inquiry into Missing and Murde