    <edge source="The question is asking why the Canadian federal government cannot provide an economic update during the uncertain times of COVID-19, when some provinces like Quebec, Saskatchewan, and Newfoundland have been able to do so.&#10;&#10;Minister Mona Fortier, the Canadian Finance Minister, has stated that the Canadian economy is going through a period of extraordinary uncertainty due to COVID-19 and that the government will continue to be open and transparent about the actions it is taking to support families, businesses, workers, and the healthcare system. However, she has not provided a clear economic projection yet. The opposition parties have criticized the government for not providing an economic update, arguing that Canadians deserve to know the state of the economy, especially given the current uncertainty caused by the pandemic.&#10;&#10;Minister Fortier has mentioned the implementation of the economic action plan to respond to COVID-19 and the provision of immediate assistance to Canadians, businesses, and workers. She has also highlighted the support provided through interest-free loans to businesses and continued support for businesses and Canadians during this time. However, she has not provided a clear answer regarding the reason for not providing an economic update.&#10;&#10;The opposition parties, including MPs Cathy McLeod, Grard Deltell, and John Williamson, have criticized the government for not providing an economic update, arguing that Canadians deserve to know the state of the economy, especially given the current uncertainty caused by the pandemic. They have pointed out that other provinces are able to provide updates on their economies while carrying out their responsibilities.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Canadian federal government has not provided a clear answer regarding why they cannot provide an economic update during these uncertain times, despite calls from opposition parties and some provinces doing so. The Finance Minister has emphasized the government's commitment to transparency and supporting Canadians but has not given a timeline for when an economic projection may be provided." target="1) The Canadian government, led by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and Finance Minister Mona Fortier, is facing pressure from opposition parties to provide an economic update during the COVID-19 pandemic. Opposition MPs argue that Canadians deserve to know the state of the economy, especially given the current uncertainty caused by the pandemic and the pre-existing economic troubles prior to COVID-19.&#10;2) Minister Fortier has acknowledged the extraordinary uncertainty due to COVID-19 and stated that the government will continue to be open and transparent about its actions. However, she has not provided a clear economic projection yet. The opposition parties have criticized the government for not providing an economic update, while some provinces like Quebec, Saskatchewan, and Newfoundland have been able to provide updates on their economies.&#10;3) Minister Fortier emphasizes the government's commitment to transparency and supporting Canadians but has not given a clear reason or timeline for when an economic projection may be provided. The opposition parties argue that the government's refusal to provide an update is a sign of a lack of transparency and accountability.">
