    <edge source="1. The current challenge faced by creators in the music industry is the significant decline in their income, despite the increased accessibility of culture and music through digital technology. This paradox can be attributed to the way the digital technology revolution has disrupted the system for distributing wealth generated by creators, with various internet stakeholders, many of whom are billionaires, benefiting instead. The petition mentioned addresses this issue by proposing a minimum royalty model for streaming platforms and requesting that telecom providers share their profits with artists since they sell their services as direct access to culture.&#10;&#10;Additionally, the Canadian government has provided support measures tailored to the arts and culture sector's needs during the COVID-19 crisis. These include adapting the CERB to consider royalties and extending it for a more extended period, acknowledging that recovery in this sector may take longer (Hon. Steven Guilbeault). The government is also consulting with arts and culture stakeholders to develop long-term solutions, though details of these efforts have not been disclosed yet (Hon. Steven Guilbeault).&#10;&#10;The challenges faced by creators in the music industry highlight a pressing need for fair compensation models that adequately reflect the value of their work in the digital era and address the issues arising from digital technology's impact on wealth distribution within the cultural ecosystem." target="ically, creators' incomes have never been so low. The advent of digital technology has completely overturned the system for distributing the wealth generated by creators for the benefit of various Web stakeholders, many of whom are billionaires. This petition addresses these problems and proposes realistic solutions. The first is to set a minimum royalty model for streaming platforms for artists. The second is to update the existing private copying system. The third is for Internet and cell phone providers who sell their services as direct access to culture to share their profits with artists. The fourth is that the GAFAMs have to pay taxes on their services. Six thousand people have already signed the first version of this petition, launched last month by musician JordanOfficer and supported by singer BarbaraSecours. As an artist, I am proud to present this petition today because the issues it raises are fundamental to the survival of Quebec culture.&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: We'll now continue with Mr. Genuis.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Garnett Genuis (Sherwood ParkFort Saskatchewan, CPC)&#10;Content: Thank you very much, Mr. Chair. I have four petitions to present today. I will be as brief as you suggested, although I will observe that if some members are going on longer">
